{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535690"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:59:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:59:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15503"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15503"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0,0.58,0.02,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8194"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89884"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8194"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74053"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2507"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43579"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89884"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after accidental exposure to chlorine gas while cleaning his swimming pool. He mixed pool chlorine with hydrochloric acid in an enclosed space. He has immediate onset of coughing, chest tightness, and difficulty breathing. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. He has widespread wheeze on chest auscultation. His conjunctivae are injected and his throat appears erythematous.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nebulised sodium bicarbonate","Empiric antibiotics","Supplemental oxygen and bronchodilators","Intravenous N-acetylcysteine","Immediate endotracheal intubation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute chlorine gas exposure after mixing pool chemicals, a common scenario that creates toxic chlorine gas. The immediate effects include irritation of the eyes, nose, throat and airways, leading to cough, wheeze and respiratory distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupplemental oxygen and bronchodilators\u003C/strong\u003E are the mainstay of initial treatment. Oxygen helps maintain adequate saturation while bronchodilators help relieve bronchospasm. The patient should also be decontaminated if necessary and removed from the source of exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised sodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E has been suggested as a treatment for chlorine gas exposure based on its potential to neutralise hydrochloric acid formed when chlorine gas contacts mucosal surfaces. However, evidence for its efficacy is limited and it is not considered standard first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous N-acetylcysteine\u003C/strong\u003E is used in paracetamol overdose and some other toxic exposures, but it has no proven benefit in chlorine gas exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate endotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for severe respiratory failure or impending respiratory arrest, but this patient, while distressed, is maintaining adequate ventilation and oxygenation with supplemental oxygen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpiric antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated as this is a chemical injury rather than an infection. The acute symptoms are due to direct chemical irritation of the airways rather than infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing initial stabilisation, the patient should be monitored for at least 24 hours as pulmonary oedema can develop in a delayed fashion. Systemic corticosteroids may be considered in severe cases to reduce airway inflammation, though evidence for their benefit is limited.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chlorine gas exposure causes acute respiratory symptoms and pulmonary oedema requiring immediate removal from the source.","Supplemental oxygen and bronchodilators are the mainstay of initial treatment for chlorine gas exposure.","Corticosteroids may be beneficial in severe chlorine gas exposure to reduce airway inflammation."],"references":["Huynh Tuong A, Despr\u00e9aux T, Loeb T, Salomon J, M\u00e9garbane B, Descatha A. Emergency management of chlorine gas exposure \u2013 a systematic review. Clinical Toxicology. 2019 Jan 23;57(2):77\u201398.","\u200cLong N. Chlorine toxicity [Internet]. Life in the Fast Lane \u2022 LITFL. 2019. Available at: https://litfl.com/chlorine-toxicity/\u200c","Hoy RF. Respiratory problems - occupational and environmental exposures. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 Nov;41(11):856-60. PMID: 23145415. [cited 2025 Mar 10] Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/944b0cdd-6293-44a6-bad4-98ce73fe397e/Respiratory-problems.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74053